<TITLE> Bollywood comes to Britain for 'Boscars' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LEEDS, June 09 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Bollywood's biggest stars are partying in northern England this weekend for the International Indian Film Awards (IIFA) -- the industry's equivalent of the Oscars. Among the screen idols in town are superstar Amitabh Bachchan, his son, Abishek and daughter-in-law Aishwarya, who have all been nominated for IIFA awards, or 'Boscars', as they are sometimes known. Starlet Shilpa Shetty, now as famous in Britain as in India after the racism row that engulfed her appearance on British reality TV show Big Brother this year, is also attending and is throwing a birthday party on Friday night in Leeds. But before that, two of the sub-continent's biggest passions were united at Headingley Stadium where Bollywood actors such as Bobby Deol and Anil Kapoor were due to take part in a charity cricket match with Indian sports stars Kapil Dev and Mohammad Azharuddin. They were to face a 'home' team that included former England players such as Devon Malcolm and Philip DeFreitas as well as Ed Balls, the right hand man of Britain's next prime minister, Gordon Brown. The action moves to Bradford on Saturday with a premiere of the film 'Dosar' before the IIFA pays a special tribute led by Amitabh Bachchan and fellow screen legend Dharmendra to the Hindi film director Hrishikesh Mukherjee who died last year. Popularly known as Hrishi-da, Mukherjee was famous for such films as 'Gol Maal' and 'Namak Haraam'. But the weekend's main event will be on Saturday night in Sheffield when the glitterati will gather for the gala awards ceremony. Among the films up for best picture are 'Dhoom 2' -- a cops and robbers musical extravaganza and 'Krrish' -- billed as India's first superhero mov
